---
import Icon from "@xtyle/astro/Icon.astro";
import Button from "@xtyle/astro/Button.astro";
import Card from "@xtyle/astro/Card.astro";
import Stack from "@xtyle/astro/Stack.astro";
import Cluster from "@xtyle/astro/Cluster.astro";
import Grid from "@xtyle/astro/Grid.astro";
import Heading from "@xtyle/astro/Heading.astro";
import Text from "@xtyle/astro/Text.astro";
import { ICON_NAMES } from "@xtyle/core";
---

<Stack gap={6}>
	<Card>
		<Heading slot="header" level={3} size="sm">The functional set</Heading>
		<Grid minColWidth="7rem" gap={3}>
			{
				ICON_NAMES.map((name) => (
					<Stack gap={1} align="center" style="text-align: center; padding: 0.75rem 0;">
						<Icon name={name} size="lg" />
						<Text tone="muted" size="xs" mono>{name}</Text>
					</Stack>
				))
			}
		</Grid>
	</Card>

	<Card>
		<Heading slot="header" level={3} size="sm">Generated marks</Heading>
		<Stack gap={3}>
			<Text tone="muted" size="sm">
				A <code>name</code> that carries a spec (a <code>--</code> grammar) is composed on the fly instead of
				looked up: primitives placed on a grid, sized, rotated, outlined, or knocked out, colored from the
				theme's own series so a mark recolors with the theme. See the grammar for the full syntax.
			</Text>
			<Grid minColWidth="8rem" gap={3}>
				{
					[
						"dice-3--square3-c1--dot-p7-s14-ko--dot-s14-ko--dot-p3-s14-ko",
						"crest--shield-c1--star-s45-cf",
						"badge--circle-c2--bolt-s52-cb",
						"target--ring-c1--dot-s28-c2",
						"framed--square-c0-o2c1--heart-s44-c2",
						"spun--diamond-c1--cross-s42-r45-cf",
						"check-badge--circle-c3--check-s55-cf",
						"search-chip--square-c0-o2c2--search-s52-c2",
						"pennant--triangle-c1-r90--divider-s60-cf",
						"split--circle-c2--divider-s70-cb",
					].map((spec) => (
						<Stack gap={1} align="center" style="text-align: center; padding: 0.75rem 0;">
							<Icon name={spec} size="xl" />
							<Text tone="muted" size="xs" mono style="word-break: break-all;">{spec.split("--")[0]}</Text>
						</Stack>
					))
				}
			</Grid>
			<Text tone="muted" size="sm">
				The same spec under a different palette via <code>colors</code>. A palette is a set of stops
				and a mark asks it for N colors, so a ramp-shaped palette (<code>thermal</code>,
				<code>severity</code>, <code>intensity</code>) is sampled just as happily as a categorical one:
			</Text>
			<Cluster gap={4} align="center">
				<Icon name="chip--hex-c1--dot-s30-c2" size="xl" colors="accents" />
				<Icon name="chip--hex-c1--dot-s30-c2" size="xl" colors="skittles" />
				<Icon name="chip--hex-c1--dot-s30-c2" size="xl" colors="statuses" />
				<Icon name="chip--hex-c1--dot-s30-c2" size="xl" colors="thermal" />
				<Icon name="chip--hex-c1--dot-s30-c2" size="xl" colors="severity" />
				<Icon name="chip--hex-c1--dot-s30-c2" size="xl" colors="intensity" />
			</Cluster>
		</Stack>
	</Card>

	<Card>
		<Heading slot="header" level={3} size="sm">A mark that carries its own palette</Heading>
		<Stack gap={3}>
			<Text tone="muted" size="sm">
				A palette reaches a mark from two places, and the narrower one wins. <code>colors</code> sets it on
				the control; a <code>---ps-&#123;palette&#125;</code> finish pins it in the <em>name</em>, so the mark
				is self-contained and colors the same wherever it lands. The flag validates against the shipped
				palette list, so every name below works with no parser change. All six icons sit under the same
				<code>colors="accents"</code> control:
			</Text>
			<Cluster gap={5} align="center">
				{
				[
					{ name: "chip--hex-c1--dot-s30-c2", tag: "no ps · inherits accents" },
					{ name: "chip--hex-c1--dot-s30-c2---ps-skittles", tag: "---ps-skittles" },
					{ name: "chip--hex-c1--dot-s30-c2---ps-thermal", tag: "---ps-thermal" },
					{ name: "chip--hex-c1--dot-s30-c2---ps-statuses", tag: "---ps-statuses" },
					{ name: "chip--hex-c1--dot-s30-c2---ps-severity", tag: "---ps-severity" },
					{ name: "chip--hex-c1--dot-s30-c2---ps-intensity", tag: "---ps-intensity" },
				].map((mark) => (
					<Stack gap={1} align="center" style="text-align: center;">
						<Icon name={mark.name} size="xl" colors="accents" />
						<Text tone="muted" size="xs" mono style="word-break: break-all;">{mark.tag}</Text>
					</Stack>
				))
				}
			</Cluster>
			<Text tone="muted" size="sm">
				A <code>pc</code> override still beats the pinned palette for the one slot it names, so a mark can
				pin the crayon box and then force a single slot to a theme token:
			</Text>
			<Cluster gap={5} align="center">
				{
				[
					{ name: "heat--ring-c1--dot-s28-c9---ps-thermal", tag: "---ps-thermal" },
					{ name: "heat--ring-c1--dot-s28-c9---ps-thermal--pc1-accent", tag: "---ps-thermal--pc1-accent" },
					{ name: "swatch--square2-c1--star-s45-c5---ps-skittles", tag: "---ps-skittles" },
					{ name: "swatch--square2-c1--star-s45-c5---ps-skittles--pc5-fg", tag: "---ps-skittles--pc5-fg" },
				].map((mark) => (
					<Stack gap={1} align="center" style="text-align: center;">
						<Icon name={mark.name} size="xl" />
						<Text tone="muted" size="xs" mono style="word-break: break-all;">{mark.tag}</Text>
					</Stack>
				))
				}
			</Cluster>
		</Stack>
	</Card>

	<Card>
		<Heading slot="header" level={3} size="sm">Text marks</Heading>
		<Stack gap={3}>
			<Text tone="muted" size="sm">
				The <code>letter</code> primitive typesets a glyph as a mark (<code>--letter-A</code>), so a
				monogram or initial composes like any other primitive: colored, framed, outlined, scaled. It
				draws in an indexed font slot (<code>-f0</code> sans, <code>-f1</code> display, <code>-f2</code>
				mono), and a <code>---f</code> finish swaps a slot for another theme font. A named web font
				renders only where it's loaded; theme-token fonts always work.
			</Text>
			<Grid minColWidth="8rem" gap={3}>
				{
					[
						"letter A--letter-A",
						"display Q--letter-Q-f1",
						"mono 7--letter-7-f2",
						"badged A--circle-c1--letter-A-cb-s55",
						"framed N--square-c0-o2c1--letter-N-c1-s55",
						"outlined R--letter-R-o2c2-s150",
					].map((spec) => (
						<Stack gap={1} align="center" style="text-align: center; padding: 0.75rem 0;">
							<Icon name={spec} size="xl" />
							<Text tone="muted" size="xs" mono style="word-break: break-all;">{spec.split("--")[0]}</Text>
						</Stack>
					))
				}
			</Grid>
		</Stack>
	</Card>

	<Card>
		<Heading slot="header" level={3} size="sm">Web fonts, on request</Heading>
		<Stack gap={3}>
			<Text tone="muted" size="sm">
				A <code>---f</code> finish can name a web font (<code>---f1-lobster</code>). The engine gates the
				family on its character set, which is what keeps an untrusted icon name from smuggling a quote
				or an angle bracket into the URL it builds. Hand it the Google Fonts list with
				<code>useGoogleFontCatalogue</code> — as the icon builder does — and it also gets exact: a typo
				reads as a typo instead of rendering in a silent fallback, and <code>ibm+plex+mono</code>
				resolves to the real <code>IBM Plex Mono</code> rather than a mis-cased guess that 404s. These
				marks render in the theme's display font until you load the family.
			</Text>
			<Grid minColWidth="8rem" gap={3} class="demo-webfont-marks">
				{
					[
						["Lobster", "lobster L--letter-L-f1---f1-lobster"],
						["Monoton", "monoton 8--circle-c3--letter-8-f1-cb-s55---f1-monoton"],
						["Bungee", "bungee B--letter-B-f1-o2c2---f1-bungee"],
						["Noto Sans Symbols", "symbols--letter-N-f1---f1-noto+sans+symbols"],
					].map(([family, spec]) => (
						<Stack gap={1} align="center" style="text-align: center; padding: 0.75rem 0;">
							<Icon name={spec} size="xl" />
							<Text tone="muted" size="xs" mono style="word-break: break-all;">{family}</Text>
						</Stack>
					))
				}
			</Grid>
			<Cluster gap={3} align="center">
				<Button size="sm" variant="subtle" id="demo-load-fonts">Load from Google Fonts</Button>
				<Text tone="subtle" size="xs" id="demo-font-status">Not loaded</Text>
			</Cluster>
			<Text tone="subtle" size="xs">
				Nothing is fetched until you click. Your browser asks <code>fonts.googleapis.com</code> for the
				font directly, which tells Google your IP address. An export does not have this problem:
				<code>embedFontsInSvg</code> bakes the face into the SVG, subsetted to just the glyphs the mark
				draws, so the file renders correctly on a machine that has never heard of the font.
			</Text>
		</Stack>
	</Card>

	<Card>
		<Heading slot="header" level={3} size="sm">Sizes</Heading>
		<Cluster gap={4} align="center" style="align-items: baseline;">
			<Icon name="search" size="sm" />
			<Icon name="search" size="md" />
			<Icon name="search" size="lg" />
			<Icon name="search" size="xl" />
		</Cluster>
	</Card>

	<Card>
		<Heading slot="header" level={3} size="sm">Tones</Heading>
		<Stack gap={3}>
			<Text tone="muted" size="sm">
				With no <code>tone</code> an icon inherits the surrounding text color; a <code>tone</code> tints
				it to a semantic role or named hue.
			</Text>
			<Cluster gap={3} align="center">
				<Icon name="success" tone="success" size="lg" />
				<Icon name="warning" tone="warn" size="lg" />
				<Icon name="error" tone="danger" size="lg" />
				<Icon name="info" tone="info" size="lg" />
				<Icon name="dot" tone="accent" size="lg" />
			</Cluster>
		</Stack>
	</Card>

	<Card>
		<Heading slot="header" level={3} size="sm">Spin</Heading>
		<Cluster gap={4} align="center">
			<Icon name="loader" spin size="lg" label="Loading" />
			<Text tone="muted" size="sm">The <code>loader</code> glyph with <code>spin</code> is a lightweight busy indicator.</Text>
		</Cluster>
	</Card>

	<Card>
		<Heading slot="header" level={3} size="sm">In controls</Heading>
		<Cluster gap={3} align="center">
			<Button><Icon name="plus" slot="icon-start" />New</Button>
			<Button variant="subtle"><Icon name="external-link" slot="icon-end" />Docs</Button>
			<Button variant="ghost" iconOnly aria-label="More"><Icon name="more-vertical" /></Button>
		</Cluster>
	</Card>

	<Card>
		<Heading slot="header" level={3} size="sm">Transport controls</Heading>
		<Stack gap={3}>
			<Text tone="muted" size="sm">
				The media-transport glyphs (<code>play</code>, <code>pause</code>, <code>stop</code>,
				<code>skip-back</code>, <code>skip-forward</code>) drop into a run bar or a player the
				same way any glyph does, so a run / execute / start-stop control renders in one voice.
			</Text>
			<Cluster gap={2} align="center">
				<Button variant="ghost" iconOnly aria-label="Skip back"><Icon name="skip-back" /></Button>
				<Button><Icon name="play" slot="icon-start" />Run</Button>
				<Button variant="subtle" iconOnly aria-label="Pause"><Icon name="pause" /></Button>
				<Button variant="subtle" iconOnly aria-label="Stop"><Icon name="stop" tone="danger" /></Button>
				<Button variant="ghost" iconOnly aria-label="Skip forward"><Icon name="skip-forward" /></Button>
			</Cluster>
		</Stack>
	</Card>

	<Card>
		<Heading slot="header" level={3} size="sm">Inline</Heading>
		<Text>
			Press the <Icon name="search" /> to search, then <Icon name="check" tone="success" /> to confirm or
			<Icon name="close" tone="danger" /> to dismiss.
		</Text>
	</Card>
</Stack>

<script>
	import { loadGoogleFont } from "@xtyle/core";

	const FAMILIES = ["Lobster", "Monoton", "Bungee", "Noto Sans Symbols"];

	function initWebFontDemo(): void {
		const button = document.querySelector<HTMLButtonElement>("#demo-load-fonts");
		const status = document.querySelector<HTMLElement>("#demo-font-status");
		if (!button || !status) return;

		button.addEventListener("click", async () => {
			button.disabled = true;
			status.textContent = "Loading…";
			const results = await Promise.allSettled(FAMILIES.map((family) => loadGoogleFont(family)));
			const failed = results.filter((r) => r.status === "rejected").length;
			status.textContent = failed ? `Loaded, ${failed} failed` : "Loaded from Google Fonts";
			button.disabled = failed === 0;
		});
	}

	document.addEventListener("astro:page-load", initWebFontDemo);
</script>
